const faqs = [
  {
    question: "Is it typical that my 7-year-old still cannot tie shoes?",
    answer: "Yes. Many typically developing children learn to tie shoes between 6 and 8 years, and some master the steps closer to age 8 because shoe tying depends on fine motor control, hand strength, bilateral coordination, and attention rather than age alone (AAP, 2020; CDC, 2022). Talk with your pediatrician if shoe tying is hard along with several other daily hand-skill tasks."
  },
  {
    question: "Should I worry if my child can do zippers but not shoelaces?",
    answer: "Usually not. Zippers are mechanically simpler than shoelaces, so a child may manage coats and backpacks before learning loops, knot tension, and crossing steps for shoe tying. If your 6–8-year-old struggles broadly with buttons, scissors, handwriting, and utensil use too, discuss it with your pediatrician (AAP, 2020)."
  },
  {
    question: "What age do most kids tie shoes independently?",
    answer: "Most children learn independent shoe tying sometime in the 6–8 year range, but the exact timing varies widely because the skill depends on practice, interest, and fine motor maturity more than a single milestone deadline (AAP, 2020). If your child is nearing 8 and is frustrated by many fine motor tasks, bring it up with your pediatrician."
  },
  {
    question: "Is it better to use Velcro if my child gets overwhelmed by laces?",
    answer: "Yes. Velcro shoes are a reasonable support for a 6–8-year-old who is still building fine motor skills, and using them does not prevent later shoe-tying success. Reducing daily stress can make practice calmer and more productive. Talk with your pediatrician if frustration is extreme or dressing skills are broadly delayed."
  },
  {
    question: "How can I teach my child to tie shoes without making it a battle?",
    answer: "The most effective approach is short, low-pressure practice with a shoe in your lap, simple steps, and frequent repetition rather than long correction-heavy sessions. Occupational therapy strategies often use backward chaining, rhyme cues, and larger laces because children learn best when success comes early (AOTA, 2021). Talk with your pediatrician if practice remains unusually hard."
  },
  {
    question: "Could trouble tying shoes mean dysgraphia or dyspraxia?",
    answer: "Sometimes, but shoe-tying difficulty alone does not diagnose anything. Persistent trouble with laces plus handwriting, cutting, buttons, utensil use, sequencing, or motor planning can occur in children with fine motor or coordination differences, including developmental coordination disorder (AAP, 2020). If several of these are present, talk with your pediatrician about evaluation."
  }
